			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-02-28T15:12:54+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">February 28, 2014 10:12 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">February 28, 2014 10:12 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/02/28/fortress-discloses-a-paper-loss-on-bitcoin/" data-title="Fortress Discloses a Paper Loss on Bitcoin" data-description="The Fortress Investment Group is the first large public company to disclose a stake in Bitcoin. It had an unrealized loss of $3.7 million at the end of the year.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Fortress Investment Group reported a paper loss of $3.7 million from investments in Bitcoin, the first large public company to disclose a stake in the volatile virtual currency.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Fortress said it bought $20 million worth of Bitcoin in 2013, according to <a href="//www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1380393/000138039314000005/fig-20131231x10k.htm" title="S.E.C. filing">a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission</a> on Thursday.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As of Dec. 31, that stake was worth less than $17 million.</p>
<div class="entry entry-related"><h4>Related Links</h4>	<div class="entry-related">
		<ul>
					<li><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/02/28/mt-gox-files-for-bankruptcy/?module=BlogPost-Title&version=Blog%20Main&contentCollection=Restructuring%20&%20Bankruptcy&action=Click&pgtype=Blogs&region=Body" title="DealBook article">Mt. Gox Files for Bankruptcy</a></li>
				</ul>
	</div>
	</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Executives at Fortress have expressed interest in Bitcoin for months, but it has been unclear just how the company might be involved with it.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ripple Labs, a budding online Bitcoin payment system, had disclosed an investment from Pantera Capital, which includes money from executives at Fortress.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Fortress filing on Thursday did not detail the exact nature of its virtual currency investment, and a spokesman for Fortress declined to comment.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Bitcoin, which exists only as computer code, has thus far circumvented the traditional financial system. That has posed a challenge for regulators, which now face increased pressure in the wake of the collapse of Mt. Gox, one of the earliest and at one point largest Bitcoin exchanges.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Fortressâs investment in Bitcoin represents a tiny fraction, less than 1 percent, of a balance sheet valued at $2.6 billion at the end of 2013. But its stake could encourage interest in an industry that has not yet gained a foothold with Wall Street or the general economy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThis makes it more legitimate for the hedge funds to buy, and easier, and provide the path for any other public company to report it,â said Gil Luria, a managing director at Wedbush Securities.  âNow, thereâs a blueprint for how to go through reporting ownership of Bitcoin in a public S.E.C. filing.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Banks have largely shied away from Bitcoin because of its volatility and lack of regulation. That has fueled Bitcoinâs instability, and the price has fluctuated wildly since the currency was introduced in 2009.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But venture capital firms and other established entrepreneurs have begun to back new Bitcoin companies with more sophisticated infrastructure and technology. Thatâs fueled some hopes that Bitcoin could gain more of a foothold in the mainstream.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI think the question now is whether theyâre going to market this as a product to their investors,â Mr. Luria said of Fortressâs investment. âI think that would be the next step I would expect from them.â</p>
	</div>
		<footer class="entry-footer">
